5.2.1 Exercises

Exercise 1

Table 1: Each observation represents a country where the number of cases and population was collected in 1999 and 2000. Each column represents the values of the variables.

Table 2: Each observation represents a variable in a country per year. The columns the country, year, and the type and counts of data.

Table 3: Each observation similarly shows the country and year data was collected. The columns represent the 2 variables country and year, as well as a rate containing number of cases and population.

Exercise 2

a) Filter âtypeâ column to only show the value âcasesâ, then get cases count

b) Do the same as above but for the value âpopulationsâ

c) Define new variable called ârateâ and make rate = case/population * 1000

d) Make new column using mutate() function with rate calculation

theme_set(theme_bw())
p <- time_series_deaths_confirmed |>
  filter (`Country/Region` %in% c("France","Afghanistan", "New Zealand","Korea, South","Egypt","Ecuador","United Kingdom", "France", "Sri Lanka", "China" )) |>
  ggplot(aes(x=`Country/Region`, y=Confirmed, color= `Country/Region`)) + 
    geom_point(aes(size=Confirmed)) + 
    transition_time(Date) + 
    labs(title = "Cumulative Deaths: {frame_time}") + 
    ylab("Deaths") +
    theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, vjust = 1, hjust=1))
animate(p, renderer = gifski_renderer(), end_pause = 15)
